\begin{align*}
(1 + x)^{1000} & = \sum_{i = 0}^{1000}\binom{1000}{i}x^i
\end{align*}
and
\begin{align*}
(1 + x)^{999} & = \sum_{i = 0}^{999}\binom{999}{i}x^i.
\end{align*}
From the second equation, let's multiply the LHS by $x$ and the RHS by $2$ to get
\begin{align*}
x(1 + x)^{999} & = \sum_{i = 0}^{999}\binom{999}{i}x^{i+1}
\end{align*}
Applying this to all the intermediate polynomials, we get
\begin{align*}
(1 + x)^{1000} + 2x(1 + x)^{999} + 3x^2(1 + x)^{998} + \dots + 1001x^{1000} & = \sum_{i = 0}^{1000}\binom{1000}{i}x^i + \sum_{i = 0}^{998}\binom{999}{i}2x^{i+1} \\
& = \sum_{i = 0}^{1000}\binom{1000}{i}x^i + \sum_{i = 0}^{997}\binom{999}{i}2x^{i+1} \\
& = \sum_{i = 0}^{1000}\binom{1000}{i}x^i + \sum_{i = 1}^{1000}\binom{999}{i - 1}2x^{i}.
\end{align*}
As you can see, the coefficient of $x^{50}$ comes from the three terms $\binom{1000}{50}, \binom{999}{49}2, \binom{999}{50}$. Hence, the coefficient of $x^{50}$ is
\begin{align*}
\binom{1000}{50} + \binom{999}{49}2 + \binom{999}{50} & = \binom{1001}{50} + \binom{999}{49}2.
\end{align*}
We will instead find the coefficient of an expression with a binomial coefficient: $\binom{1001}{50}.$ By tests out, we find
\[\binom{1000}{50} + \binom{999}{50} = \binom{1001}{50}.\]Also, $\binom{999}{49} = \binom{1000}{50}.$ So our coefficient is $\boxed{2\binom{1001}{50}}$. Its value is $\binom{1001}{50} + \binom{1001}{50} = 2\binom{1001}{50}.$
Thus, we have $n = 1001, k = 50,$ and $n + k = \boxed{1051}.$</answer>

